Carbon nanomaterials (CNMs) demonstrate significant advantages over conventional adsorbents such as activated carbon, particularly in pharmaceutical waste remediation. These advantages stem from CNMs' superior surface area, customizable surface functionalities, and enhanced catalytic properties (Table 5
                     ) and Table 6
                      provides a comparative analysis of types of CNMs summarizing removal efficiencies [129]. For instance, MWCNTs and GO have demonstrated a greater capacity to adsorb drugs such as ibuprofen, diclofenac, and various antibiotics than activated carbon. Functionalization of CNMs with specific chemical groups enhances their selectivity and interaction with pharmaceutical contaminants, improving performance [130]. Regarding degradation efficiency, CNMs, particularly GO and CDs, possess photocatalytic properties that facilitate not only adsorption but also the degradation of pharmaceuticals under visible light—a capability traditional adsorbents lack. This dual functionality offers a significant advantage for pharmaceutical waste remediation [131,132]. While CNM production costs are initially higher, their extended lifespan, reusability, and efficiency per unit of material contribute to long-term cost-effectiveness. CNMs' capacity for selective adsorption minimizes material requirements, reduces operational costs, and enhances overall performance in pharmaceutical waste treatment [133].
